Git & GitHub

1. What is Git?
- Git is a version control system used to track changes in files.
- Helps teams collaborate and manage code versions.

2. What is GitHub?
- GitHub is an online hosting platform for Git repositories.
- Used for collaboration, backups, and project sharing.

3. Install Git
- Check Git version:
  git --version

4. Configure Git
  git config --global user.name "Your Name"
  git config --global user.email "your@email.com"

5. Create a Local Repository
  mkdir myproject
  cd myproject
  git init

6. Create and Track Files
  touch index.html
  git status
  git add index.html
  git commit -m "Initial commit"

7. Connect Local Repo to GitHub
  git remote add origin https://github.com/username/repo.git
  git branch -M main
  git push -u origin main

8. Basic Commands
  git add .
  git commit -m "message"
  git push
  git pull
  git log

9. Branching
  git checkout -b feature1
  git checkout main
  git merge feature1
  git branch -d feature1

10. Common Errors
- Remote exists: git remote remove origin
- Nothing to commit: make changes first
- Branch not found: git branch -a

11. Student Practice Guidelines
- Create weekly repositories
- Push commits daily
- Practice branching
- Collaborate with peers


